   =20
      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

We have talked a lot recently about the takeover battle at publicly traded =
hedge fund manager Sculptor Capital Management Inc., which is in a weird li=
mbo. In July, Sculptor=E2=80=99s board agreed to sell the company to Rithm =
Capital Corp. for $11.15 per share.=C2=A0Since then, a group of hedge fund =
managers led by Boaz Weinstein has offered to buy Sculptor for $12.76 per s=
hare, which is more.
But Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has declined to engage with Weinstein and frie=
nds, arguing that their offer is less certain than Rithm=E2=80=99s.=C2=A0In=
 particular, either deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0Weinstein=E2=80=99s or Rithm=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0would require a majority of Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge-fu=
nd clients (the limited partners in its funds)=C2=A0to consent to the new m=
anagement, and Sculptor argues that its clients will like the Rithm deal (w=
hich will leave Sculptor=E2=80=99s current chief executive officer and chie=
f investment officer, Jimmy Levin, in charge of running its funds) but won=
=E2=80=99t accept the Weinstein deal (which will presumably put Weinstein a=
nd friends in charge of the funds). Therefore, Sculptor says, Weinstein=E2=
=80=99s deal isn=E2=80=99t real: If it took that deal, clients would say no=
, the deal wouldn=E2=80=99t close, Weinstein would walk away, shareholders =
wouldn=E2=80=99t get their $12.76, and Rithm would no longer be there to pa=
y $11.15. Better to take a safe $11.15 than a risky $12.76.
Now. This analysis might be correct, and it might not be. You don=E2=80=99t=
 have to believe it. For instance, Dan Och, Sculptor=E2=80=99s estranged fo=
under, and Rob Shafir, its former CEO, have both put out public statements =
saying that they don=E2=80=99t support the Rithm deal. Shafir   said that =
=E2=80=9Cit is not credible=E2=80=9D to think that Sculptor=E2=80=99s clien=
ts would not accept the Weinstein deal, and Och   has=C2=A0argued that the =
board is selling out shareholder interests in order to protect Jimmy Levin=
=E2=80=99s job.=C2=A0
(Also, I   have   suggested that this analysis is easy to test:=C2=A0Just g=
et, like, Levin and Weinstein and Rithm together in a room and have them ca=
ll Sculptor=E2=80=99s biggest investors and ask what they think! If all the=
 investors say =E2=80=9Cno, can=E2=80=99t stand that Weinstein guy,=E2=80=
=9D then (1) the board can credibly continue to reject the Weinstein deal a=
nd (2) Weinstein won=E2=80=99t want to keep pursuing it, since he doesn=E2=
=80=99t want to pay for Sculptor and get no clients.)
More generally, if you are a Sculptor=C2=A0shareholder, you might be skepti=
cal of the board=E2=80=99s analysis, just because $12.76 really is more tha=
n $11.15. There are two offers here, one for $11.15 and one for $12.76, and=
 you would much rather get the $12.76 one. The board says that the $12.76 o=
ne is a mirage, that it won=E2=80=99t actually close, but wouldn=E2=80=99t =
you be pretty tempted? Shareholders are: The stock has traded above $11.15 =
for the last three weeks or so, and closed yesterday at $12.02, suggesting =
that shareholders expect to do better than Rithm=E2=80=99s deal.
But what can anyone=C2=A0do? The board has signed a deal with Rithm and app=
arently won=E2=80=99t negotiate with Weinstein,  saying that it =E2=80=9Cha=
s not concluded that the Consortium=E2=80=99s most recent revised proposal =
constitutes a superior proposal or is reasonably expected to lead to a supe=
rior proposal.=E2=80=9D Traditionally, when a company has a signed merger a=
greement, another bidder wants to pay more, and the company won=E2=80=99t l=
et it, there are three ways to get around the board:
=09A tender offer: The other bidder (Weinstein) could, in theory, just go o=
ut to Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders with a public offer to pay $12.76 per=
 share in cash. The shareholders would rather get $12.76 than $11.15, they=
=E2=80=99ll sell to Weinstein, and he=E2=80=99ll buy the company, without t=
he board=E2=80=99s approval.
  [1]
=C2=A0But this option is off the table here. For one thing, in the course o=
f his earlier discussions with Sculptor, Weinstein apparently signed a nond=
isclosure agreement with a standstill provision, in which he promised not t=
o make a public offer for Sculptor or even to buy more stock, so he=E2=80=
=99s not allowed to tender. Also, though, Weinstein=E2=80=99s offer really=
=C2=A0is=C2=A0contingent on getting approval from Sculptor=E2=80=99s limite=
d partners =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board is not wrong about that =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and so even without the standstill he wouldn=E2=80=99t want to buy all of S=
culptor only to find out that he couldn=E2=80=99t run its funds. He is not =
going to just unconditionally buy all the shares.=09The shareholder vote: E=
ven if Sculptor=E2=80=99s board ignores Weinstein and proceeds with the Rit=
hm deal, it needs to submit the deal to a shareholder vote, and the deal ca=
n=E2=80=99t close unless a majority of shareholders votes in favor.
  [2]
=C2=A0The shareholders who want the Weinstein deal can just vote no; if the=
y mostly vote no then the Rithm deal disappears. This doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0=
necessarily=C2=A0mean that they get the Weinstein deal: Sculptor can keep i=
gnoring Weinstein and continue as an independent public company, and Weinst=
ein=E2=80=99s current proposal is not really binding, so he could just say =
=E2=80=9Cactually now my bid is $11.50=E2=80=9D if the Rithm deal fails. Th=
ere are risks. But realistically if the shareholders vote down the Rithm de=
al, the next thing that happens is probably that Sculptor starts taking Wei=
nstein=E2=80=99s calls.=09You can always sue.

Somebody   sued:

Sculptor Capital Management Inc. executives were accused in a lawsuit of en=
gineering a proposed $639 million acquisition of the fund by rival Rithm Ca=
pital Corp. in a way that is unfairly blocking a higher bid.
Chief Executive Officer Jimmy Levin and other directors shortchanged invest=
ors by using non-disclosure agreements tied to the deal to prevent stockhol=
ders from considering a higher offer from a group led by Boaz Weinstein tha=
t includes billionaires Bill Ackman, Marc Lasry and Jeff Yass, Sculptor inv=
estor Gilles Beauchemin said Monday in a Delaware Chancery Court lawsuit. S=
till, such non-disclosure pacts are common in big US merger and acquisition=
 agreements.
The Sculptor board is breaching legal duties to shareholders =E2=80=9Cby co=
ntinuing to block the topping bid and issuing disparaging disclosures=E2=80=
=9D about the rival offer, according to the suit.

We have   talked about this tension =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CStill, such non=
-disclosure pacts are common in big US merger and acquisition agreements=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94 before. On the one hand, yes, it is normal in an M&A proce=
ss to ask potential bidders to sign NDAs with standstill provisions=C2=A0th=
at prevent them from making a public topping bid; that=E2=80=99s how you ge=
t the best price in your auction. On the other hand, sure, once you get a t=
opping bid it is kind of rough to ignore it.
Here is  the lawsuit, which is pretty normal stuff. It cites a  2007 Delawa=
re case in which Topps Co. agreed to sell itself to Michael Eisner (in a de=
al that would keep Topps=E2=80=99s management), but then Upper Deck Co. cam=
e in with a topping bid; Topps refused to negotiate with Upper Deck, arguin=
g that its offer was too conditional. Because Upper Deck had signed a stand=
still agreement, it couldn=E2=80=99t make a public tender offer. The court =
found that =E2=80=9Cthere is no reasonable basis for permitting the Topps b=
oard to deny its stockholders the chance to consider for themselves whether=
 to prefer Upper Deck=E2=80=99s higher-priced deal, taking into account its=
 unique risks, over Eisner=E2=80=99s lower-priced deal, which has its own r=
isks.=E2=80=9D Similarly, here, the lawsuit argues
  [3]
:

The Topps board made the same type of excuses as the Special Committee is m=
aking here as to why it would not declare the topping bid reasonably likely=
 to lead to a Superior Proposal, including limits on liability in the event=
 the transaction did not close and regulatory issues. The Court found the T=
opps board=E2=80=99s decision not to deem Upper Deck=E2=80=99s offer reason=
ably likely to lead to a Superior Proposal =E2=80=9Chighly questionable.=E2=
=80=9D
The Topps situation similarly involved a chief executive, like Defendant Le=
vin, who had strong interests in maintaining his current position. In Topps=
, the CEO Shorin =E2=80=9Cwas motivated to find a buyer who was friendly to=
 him and would guarantee that Shorin and Silverstein, his son-in-law, would=
 continue to play leading roles at Topps.=E2=80=9D Levin has been paid almo=
st $200 million in the past two years and has ample incentive to resist a t=
ransaction that will eventually oust him. Rithm has promised to retain Levi=
n while the Consortium has indicated Levin=E2=80=99s retention is less impo=
rtant. In fact, the Consortium=E2=80=99s recent concession to=C2=A0keep Lev=
in after closing appears to have been intended to respond to the Special Co=
mmittee identifying Levin=E2=80=99s continuation as linked to deal certaint=
y. The Special Committee, aligning with Levin=E2=80=99s interests, effectiv=
ely communicated that unless Levin keeps his job, the Special Committee wil=
l consider the deal subject to undue execution risk because it will risk ob=
taining client consents. ...
The Topps decision also discussed how a standstill can operate to unfairly =
prevent a bidder from communicating with stockholders. As the Topps Court n=
oted, while they have legitimate uses, =E2=80=9Cstandstills are also subjec=
t to abuse. Parties like Eisner often, as was done here, insist on a stands=
till as a deal protection. Furthermore, a standstill can be used by a targe=
t improperly to favor one bidder over=C2=A0another, not for reasons consist=
ent with stockholder interest, but because managers prefer one bidder for t=
heir own motives.=E2=80=9D

I am not sure that the most likely outcome here is that a court will order =
Sculptor to take Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal or anything, but the point of all=
 of this is to make it unpleasant and embarrassing for the board not to neg=
otiate with Weinstein, so that either (1) they do or (2) Rithm raises its b=
id. For=C2=A0me, the fun in the Sculptor situation is that it is a bunch of=
 big hedge fund managers sniping at each other. But for Sculptor shareholde=
rs, all that matters is getting more money.

 =20
   =20
      Bank capital complaints
   =20
 =20

The way bank capital rules work is that regulators consider various possibl=
e activities that banks do, and then specify how much capital a bank needs =
for each sort of activity.=C2=A0Make $100 of corporate loans, you need like=
 $8 of capital. Buy $100 of Treasury bills, you need $0 of capital. Buy $10=
0 of Bitcoin, you need $100 of capital. That sort of thing.
  [4]

Occasionally the regulators change the rules, generally to require=C2=A0mor=
e=C2=A0capital. Conceptually, if you are a bank, there are two possible obj=
ections to the new rules:
=09The new rules require more capital, and more capital is bad. Right now (=
before the new rules) banks have enough capital: They are safe, and if bad =
stuff happens the banks will all be fine. Requiring them to add more capita=
l would be unnecessary; it would also be expensive, lowering their return o=
n equity and making the business of banking less attractive, which will lea=
d to less lending and economic contraction.=09The new rules require too muc=
h capital for some activities (and, implicitly, too little for others). The=
 new rules will=C2=A0distort=C2=A0banking activity, treating safe things as=
 risky and risky things as safe; they will make banks make bad economic dec=
isions in order to get better capital treatment.

The second objection is more intellectually interesting; it=E2=80=99s the s=
ort of thing that, if you say it to a regulator, they might say =E2=80=9Chu=
h okay you=E2=80=99re right.=E2=80=9D The first objection is probably close=
r to the hearts of most bank CEOs. They want to be able to do more stock bu=
ybacks!
Anyway the Federal Reserve   has proposed to modify US banks=E2=80=99 capit=
al requirements, and big banks have raised both sorts of objections. There =
are nuanced technical objections about how the proposed rules  get things w=
rong:

Alastair Borthwick, Bank of America=E2=80=99s chief financial officer, adde=
d to the criticism on Monday, saying the Fed=E2=80=99s proposals could mean=
 risk-weighted assets are double counted in some instances, which could aga=
in constrain bank lending.
=E2=80=9CI think there=E2=80=99s going to be some important points of advoc=
acy on the part of industry and by businesses in America, who are the ones =
who ultimately are going to pay for this,=E2=80=9D Borthwick told the Barcl=
ays conference.

And then there is Jamie Dimon complaining that   more capital is too much:

Jamie Dimon again took aim at higher capital requirements US regulators pro=
posed for the banking industry in July, saying he would =E2=80=9Clove to kn=
ow what they really want to accomplish.=E2=80=9D
Requiring US lenders to hold more capital than their international competit=
ors is a =E2=80=9Chuge negative=E2=80=9D over time, the JPMorgan Chase & Co=
. chief executive officer said Monday at a conference hosted by Barclays Pl=
c. Regulators should have shared more about the =E2=80=9Ccost-benefit to so=
ciety,=E2=80=9D said Dimon, who questioned whether they learned the right l=
essons from the failures earlier this year of Silicon Valley Bank and First=
 Republic Bank.

And:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CDo [regulators] want banks ever to be investable again?=E2=80=9D D=
imon said at an industry conference organised by Barclays. =E2=80=9CI would=
n=E2=80=99t be a big buyer of banks=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89I=
=E2=80=99d be no better than equal weight, or whatever you call it,=E2=80=
=9D he told the audience of analysts and investors.
I love that Jamie Dimon obviously=C2=A0can=C2=A0speak in the language of se=
ll-side stock analysts, but he finds it somewhat distasteful. =E2=80=9CEqua=
l weight, or whatever you call it.=E2=80=9D Also he is skeptical about thos=
e =E2=80=9Cimportant points of advocacy=E2=80=9D:

The Fed is now soliciting comments on the proposed changes in a notice of p=
roposed rulemaking (NPR) but Dimon was sceptical that any material changes =
would be made.
=E2=80=9CDo you think the NPRs are going to make a =E2=80=A6 difference?=E2=
=80=9D Dimon said, in his characteristically blunt style.
  [5]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s my academics arguing with their academics. They=
=E2=80=99re going to do what they want anyway. That=E2=80=99s all that=E2=
=80=99s going to happen.=E2=80=9D

The basic point here is that the nuances might get fixed, but US banks will=
 still have to have more capital, and Dimon doesn=E2=80=99t like that.

 =20
   =20
      2x levered Bitcoin ETF
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about how the US Securities and Exchange Commission h=
as allowed futures-based Bitcoin exchange-traded funds, but has so far bloc=
ked spot Bitcoin ETFs, but that will probably change after the SEC lost a c=
ourt challenge brought by Grayscale Investments LLC. That means that there =
will probably soon be spot Bitcoin ETFs, which will be simpler and cheaper =
than Bitcoin futures ETFs, so investors who want Bitcoin ETFs will probably=
 switch. This is sad for the people who quite cleverly invented Bitcoin fut=
ures ETFs as a way around the SEC=E2=80=99s opposition, and who will soon h=
ave a clever product that no one wants. There is hope for them, though. I w=
rote:
If you run a Bitcoin futures ETF, and you see the spot Bitcoin ETFs coming =
for you, are you at least considering opening a 2x levered Bitcoin ETF? I=
=E2=80=99m sure the SEC would love that.
Well, that last sentence was sarcastic. The SEC seems to me to be skeptical=
 of all crypto; it kind of thinks that Bitcoin is just gambling, which make=
s a 2x Bitcoin ETF double gambling. But a=C2=A0reader pointed out that  Vol=
atility Shares already did this, and the SEC approved it:
The 2x Bitcoin Strategy ETF (Ticker: BITX) seeks to provide daily investmen=
t results, before fees and expenses, that correspond generally to twice the=
 performance of the S&P CME Bitcoin Futures Daily Roll Index (Ticker: SPBTF=
DUE) for a single day, not for any other period. The fund does not invest d=
irectly in bitcoin. Instead, the Fund seeks to benefit from increases in th=
e price of Bitcoin Futures Contracts for a single day.
The SEC doesn=E2=80=99t want to make it too easy to invest in Bitcoin via E=
TFs, but, due to its own odd logic, it has made it possible to invest in=C2=
=A0double=C2=A0Bitcoin via ETFs.=C2=A0
By the way, as part of its legal challenge to the SEC, Grayscale complained=
 about this irony in a letter to the court:

The 2x Bitcoin Strategy ETF, which seeks to double the performance of the S=
&P CME Bitcoin Futures Daily Roll Index each day, is leveraged. As a result=
, it exposes investors to an even riskier investment product than tradition=
al bitcoin futures exchange-traded products (=E2=80=9CETPs=E2=80=9D), which=
 encompass risks related to both the futures and spot bitcoin markets. ...
The fact that the Commission has allowed a leveraged bitcoin futures ETP to=
=C2=A0begin trading demonstrates that the Commission continues to arbitrari=
ly treat spot bitcoin ETPs differently than bitcoin futures ETPs. =E2=80=A6=
 The 2x Bitcoin Strategy ETF is therefore exposed to even more risks of the=
 bitcoin markets than Grayscale=E2=80=99s proposed spot bitcoin ETP.

If you worry about spot Bitcoin ETFs because you think the Bitcoin market i=
s manipulated, well, a 2x Bitcoin ETF is twice as manipulated.

