  [1] This is a bit of an exaggeration, since boards can block tender offer=
s with=20
a poison pill, but it would be hard to justify in the face of an unconditio=
nal higher all-cash tender offer.


  [2] There are actually two vote requirements in this deal. One (imposed b=
y corporate law) is that a majority of shares has to vote yes; the other (i=
mposed by Sculptor=E2=80=99s board) is that a majority of shares held by th=
e =E2=80=9CNon-Unitholder Stockholders=E2=80=9D has to vote yes. The latter=
 vote basically excludes insiders (like Jimmy Levin) from the vote, but it =
also excludes former insiders (like Dan Och); it is, roughly, a vote of the=
 disinterested outside shareholders. My rough count is that current insider=
s (Levin et al.) own about 27% of the votes and disgruntled ex-insiders (Oc=
h, Shafir) own perhaps half that, so it will be a bit harder for Sculptor t=
o win the second vote of disinterested outsiders.


  [3] Citations omitted.


  [4] These numbers are not meant to be precise or anything, but the tradit=
ional rule of thumb is that =E2=80=9Cthe=E2=80=9D capital ratio is 8% of ri=
sk-weighted assets. Corporate loans have a 100% risk weight, Treasuries 0%,=
=20
crypto 1,250%. Modern capital regulation also has a =E2=80=9Cleverage ratio=
=E2=80=9D requirement that is designed to backstop risk-weighted capital ru=
les by providing a crude minimum capital requirement that is consistent acr=
oss all exposures, but in practice those rules get pretty complicated too.


  [5] I omitted the bluntness.


