<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Historically, retail stock investing was a bun=
dle of:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">a sensible way to invest for retiremen=
t by buying a share of the future earnings of big businesses, and</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">fun gambling.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was just a very strong case that, if you=
 wanted to make long-term retirement investments, buying stocks was the <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32686879.258425/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93c3Aud2hhcnRvbi51cGVubi5lZHUvYm9vay9zdG9ja3MtZm9yLXRoZS1sb25nLXJ1bi8/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4bcf5751" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> good and sensible</a> way to do=
 it, endorsed by academic theory and common sense. But you had to pick the =
stocks: In the olden days, stock investing meant=C2=A0<em>buying individual=
 stocks</em>, and retail stock investing meant=C2=A0<em>not buying that man=
y of them,=C2=A0</em>because stocks traded in round lots of 100 expensive s=
hares so you could only buy so many different stocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you wanted exposure to the future earnin=
gs of the widget business, you probably bought either Amalgamated Widgets o=
r Consolidated Widgets, but not a market-cap-weighted combination of both. =
You consciously=C2=A0<em>chose=C2=A0</em>one of them =E2=80=94=C2=A0based o=
n how much you liked its product or advertisements or logo or name=C2=A0or =
ticker or media-friendly CEO or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then had sort o=
f a rooting interest in your chosen stock. You could follow along, pay atte=
ntion to what your stocks were doing, watch them rise or fall on earnings r=
eports, adjust your portfolio over time to refine your bets. For many peopl=
e this was an annoying and intimidating chore. For others, though, it was a=
 fun hobby and a way to, potentially, make a lot of money quickly by making=
 the right bets. It scratched some of the same itches as sports or casino g=
ambling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rise of mutual funds and, especially, inde=
x investing changed that. Now if you want to make sensible long-term retire=
ment investments, everyone will still tell you to own stocks, but not <em>p=
articular=C2=A0</em>stocks. They will tell you to own stocks by buying and =
holding low-cost broad market index funds and trying not to look at your ac=
count much. Picking individual stocks, frequent trading and paying attentio=
n to the market are all disfavored by the modern consensus. Now the sensibl=
e form of long-term stock investing is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32686879.258425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTAtMDMvdGhlLXJvbWFudGljLWJhY2tsYXNoLXRvLWJvcmluZy1yb=
2JvdC1pbnZlc3Rpbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFp=
bCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTEyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25=
leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d383533" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  pretty dull</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can still gamble on stocks though! Whateve=
r, go nuts, no one will stop you. But as sensible equity investing for reti=
rement has been unbundled from gambling on stocks, the gambling has survive=
d and=C2=A0become purer. If you want to take a flutter on a stock to feel a=
live, that stock is probably not going to be an electric utility. There is =
a sort of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32686879=
.258425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW52ZXN0b3BlZGlhLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9pbnZlc3RpbmcvMDE=
zMTE0L2JhcmJlbGwtaW52ZXN0bWVudC1zdHJhdGVneS5hc3A/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
07458b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> barbell</a> effect: People do their sensible retirement s=
avings in the most sensible way, with boring index funds, and they do their=
 fun stock gambling in the most fun way, with meme stocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or not even with stocks. Crypto. Or, these day=
s, options. Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/32686879.258425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3N0b2Nrcy9vcHRpb25=
zLWluZGl2aWR1YWwtaW52ZXN0b3JzLXJpc2stZ2FtYmxpbmctYTk3YmVlMWE_bW9kPWhwX2xlYW=
RfcG9zNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2146b9c3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal st=
ory</a> about retail investors buying short-dated options. There is a quote=
 from an academic with the standard criticism:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe should stop pretending=
 that=E2=80=99s what=E2=80=99s going on is investing,=E2=80=9D said Benjami=
n Edwards, a professor at the University of Nevada in Las Vegas who has stu=
died securities law. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just gambling.=E2=80=9D</p></blo=
ckquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact nobody is pretending! Everyone int=
erviewed in the article is like =E2=80=9Coh yes this is my fun gambling hob=
by=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kyle Klett, 31, said he has made some painful =
trades over the past two years, including a string of mistimed one-day opti=
ons that cost him tens of thousands of dollars. Still, he said, the big win=
s have enticed him to keep trading.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late June, during a stint in Las Vegas play=
ing in the World Series of Poker, Klett said, he scooped up more than 300 c=
ontracts that would pay off if the S&amp;P 500 index rallied by the next da=
y. After he spent a sleepless night checking the futures market for clues o=
n what would happen in the morning, he said, the S&amp;P 500 rose 1.2% and =
he made $71,000.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He celebrated the big win=E2=80=94and his birt=
hday=E2=80=94by playing roulette and slot machines while hopping from casin=
o to casino on the Las Vegas Strip. =E2=80=9CI lost $25,000 in poker but sm=
oked the market,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Lucas] Sommer, the Oregon entrepreneur, said =
he has been trading options regularly since 2018. He has experienced exhila=
rating highs and painful losses, he said, and has had more than one convers=
ation with his wife about big money-losing trades.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been addicted to this op=
tions stuff for quite some time,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou get hooked.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He does most of his options trading on Robinho=
od, in what he considers his =E2=80=9Cgambling account,=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=9CYou now have the power to gamble in your pocket,=E2=80=9D he said,=
 comparing the market to a casino. His long-term investments are with anoth=
er brokerage. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou hit black, double down, black, do=
uble down, black, double down,=E2=80=9D Sommer said. Then, =E2=80=9Cred, yo=
u=E2=80=99re at zero.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, in the olden days, he=E2=80=99d have al=
l his money with one brokerage, and it would be his retirement money, and h=
e=E2=80=99d have a little fun making trades with some of it. In modern time=
s, his retirement money is somewhere safe and boring, and he quite self-con=
sciously gambles on options.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, there=E2=80=99s a barbell componen=
t to how the financial industry makes money, too. In the olden days, broker=
s charged high commissions for doing stock trades, and later mutual funds c=
harged high fees for managing your stocks for you. In the modern market, yo=
ur index exchange-traded fund charges teeny tiny fees and doesn=E2=80=99t d=
o much trading. But if you want to gamble on options you will pay up:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street firms profit on such trading. So-c=
alled bid-ask spreads=E2=80=94the difference between buy and sell prices in=
 the open market=E2=80=94are much wider for options than for stocks. Profes=
sional trading firms such as Citadel Securities and Susquehanna Internation=
al Group that buy and sell such options to investors pocket some of that di=
fference. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brokerages made more than $2 billion from sell=
ing options orders last year, more than double what they made from stock or=
ders, according to Bloomberg Intelligence data.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sensible, reasonable, academically endorse=
d best practice for retirement savings is to save money on fees. But if you=
=E2=80=99re gambling, the casino is going to make money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What should you think about this? What is the =
right regulatory response? It is tempting to say, like, =E2=80=9CI am shock=
ed, shocked to find gambling in the stock market.=E2=80=9D The US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/32686879.258425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTkvdHJhZGluZy1nYW1pZmljYXRpb24tY29uY2Vybi1mb3Itc2VjLWVuZm=
9yY2VtZW50LWNoaWVmLXNheXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1b=
T1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTEyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWln=
bj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7b94b9d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> expressed conc=
ern</a> about the gamification of stock markets, and has cracked down on pe=
ople make gambling/investing=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>fun. One objection to m=
odern commission-free trading is that it leads to more gambling behavior. (=
Also it is made possible by payment for order flow, and brokers get paid mo=
re for options order flow, which makes them more likely to push options tra=
ding.) Zero-day options strike some people as largely retail gambling produ=
cts that don=E2=80=99t serve much capital-formation or risk-hedging purpose=
. Maybe all of it should be banned.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I don=E2=80=99t know? As gambling markets =
go, the stock (and options) market has some attractive features. Insider tr=
ading is illegal, and the rules are enforced. Brokers don=E2=80=99t general=
ly steal customers=E2=80=99 money. The stock market rewards skill. It lower=
s the cost of capital for actual businesses. The people in this article, th=
e people saying =E2=80=9Cyou=C2=A0hit black, double down, black, double dow=
n, black, double down=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CI lost $25,000 in poker but smo=
ked the market,=E2=80=9D those people are going to gamble=C2=A0<em>somewher=
e</em>. Maybe it=E2=80=99s for the best that they gamble on options.</p>
