<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a lot recently about the takeov=
er battle at publicly traded hedge fund manager Sculptor Capital Management=
 Inc., which is in a weird limbo. In July, Sculptor=E2=80=99s board agreed =
to sell the company to Rithm Capital Corp. for $11.15 per share.=C2=A0Since=
 then, a group of hedge fund managers led by Boaz Weinstein has offered to =
buy Sculptor for $12.76 per share, which is more.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has declined to e=
ngage with Weinstein and friends, arguing that their offer is less certain =
than Rithm=E2=80=99s.=C2=A0In particular, either deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0Weinst=
ein=E2=80=99s or Rithm=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0would require a majority of=
 Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge-fund clients (the limited partners in its funds)=
=C2=A0to consent to the new management, and Sculptor argues that its client=
s will like the Rithm deal (which will leave Sculptor=E2=80=99s current chi=
ef executive officer and chief investment officer, Jimmy Levin, in charge o=
f running its funds) but won=E2=80=99t accept the Weinstein deal (which wil=
l presumably put Weinstein and friends in charge of the funds). Therefore, =
Sculptor says, Weinstein=E2=80=99s deal isn=E2=80=99t real: If it took that=
 deal, clients would say no, the deal wouldn=E2=80=99t close, Weinstein wou=
