<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way bank capital rules work is that regula=
tors consider various possible activities that banks do, and then specify h=
ow much capital a bank needs for each sort of activity.=C2=A0Make $100 of c=
orporate loans, you need like $8 of capital. Buy $100 of Treasury bills, yo=
u need $0 of capital. Buy $100 of Bitcoin, you need $100 of capital. That s=
ort of thing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Occasionally the regulators change the rules, =
generally to require=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>capital. Conceptually, if you =
are a bank, there are two possible objections to the new rules:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new rules require more capital, a=
nd more capital is bad. Right now (before the new rules) banks have enough =
capital: They are safe, and if bad stuff happens the banks will all be fine=
. Requiring them to add more capital would be unnecessary; it would also be=
 expensive, lowering their return on equity and making the business of bank=
ing less attractive, which will lead to less lending and economic contracti=
on.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new rules require too much=
 capital for some activities (and, implicitly, too little for others). The =
new rules will=C2=A0<em>distort=C2=A0</em>banking activity, treating safe t=
hings as risky and risky things as safe; they will make banks make bad econ=
omic decisions in order to get better capital treatment.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second objection is more intellectually in=
teresting; it=E2=80=99s the sort of thing that, if you say it to a regulato=
r, they might say =E2=80=9Chuh okay you=E2=80=99re right.=E2=80=9D The firs=
t objection is probably closer to the hearts of most bank CEOs. They want t=
o be able to do more stock buybacks!</p>
