i9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQwNTk1L255MjAwMDk5=
Mzl4MV9wcmVtMTRhLmh0bSN0Vk5F/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd24722dc" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">two=
 vote requirements</a> in this deal. One (imposed by corporate law) is that=
 a majority of shares has to vote yes; the other (imposed by Sculptor=E2=80=
=99s board) is that a majority of shares held by the =E2=80=9CNon-Unitholde=
r Stockholders=E2=80=9D has to vote yes. The latter vote basically excludes=
 insiders (like Jimmy Levin) from the vote, but it also excludes former ins=
iders (like Dan Och); it is, roughly, a vote of the disinterested outside s=
hareholders. My <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32=
686879.258425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyN=
